          "body": "Jeremiah 9 opens with one of the most psychologically acute moments in the prophetic literature. The prophet wishes simultaneously to weep without ceasing for the slain of his people (9:1) and to abandon those same people entirely (9:2). These two desires are not contradictions — they are the two poles of a love that has been violated. The first verse discloses a man of such deep covenantal sorrow that he wishes he could generate infinite tears; the second discloses a man so repulsed by the community's moral collapse that he wants to be anywhere else. He cannot stay with a people he cannot stand, and he cannot leave a people he cannot stop loving. This is the prophet's characteristic burden — what Abraham Heschel called the 'divine pathos' internalized by God's messengers. The description of the people in 9:2 is unsparing: 'all of them are adulterers' — the covenantal term for spiritual unfaithfulness — 'an assembly of treacherous men.' These are not individuals who have lapsed; it is the community's defining character."
