          "title": "The one legitimate boast (9:23-24)",
          "body": "Verses 23-24 are the theological apex of the chapter and arguably one of the most concentrated theological statements in the entire Old Testament. Three human capitals are dismantled: wisdom, might, and riches — the three pillars on which ancient near-eastern civilization built its confidence, and on which every subsequent civilization has done the same. Jeremiah does not merely say these are insufficient; he says they are illegitimate grounds of boasting — they displace the only legitimate one. The positive command of 9:24 defines what knowing God means: it is knowing that He is the LORD who exercises *chesed* (covenant loyalty), *mishpat* (justice), and *tsedaqah* (righteousness) on earth. These three attributes are not abstractions; they are relational and historical — God exercises them *in the earth*, in the same historical arena where Judah's deceit and the coming devastation are occurring. The climax of the verse is stunning: 'for I delight in these things.' The judgment throughout the chapter is not God acting against His nature; it is God acting according to His delights. *Mishpat* and *tsedaqah* demanded that the deceitful be punished; *chesed* demanded that the refining furnace be offered before the sentence was finalized. Paul quotes this verse in 1 Corinthians 1:31 and 2 Corinthians 10:17 in his argument against boasting in human wisdom — the apostle reads Jeremiah 9:24 as the permanent structure of covenantal epistemology."
